{
  "texts": [
    "The process of moral growth includes three stages: (1) instinctive or habitual action, (2) action under the stress of attention with conscious intervention and reconstruction, and (3) organization of consciously directed conduct into habits that constitutes a higher-order self or character.",
    "Habit is the central concept in Dewey's moral philosophy.",
    "The essence of Dewey's habit is \"to permit the stream of action to flow without interruption, bringing with it the satisfactions which human needs demand\" (Murphey, 2008, p. xii).",
    "Habit is rich in connotations, encompassing social and natural environments, as well as individual perceptions and behaviors (Murphey, 2008, pp. xi-xii).",
    "To a certain extent, it can even be equated with or determine one's culture and worldview."
  ]
}